  "prompt": "What is the best way of combining multiple jpegs into one jpeg/PDF on Mac OS X?",
  "response": "Combining multiple JPEG images into a single JPEG or PDF on macOS is a straightforward process. Here are the best methods:\n\n### Using Preview (Built-in App)\n1. **Open the JPEGs in Preview**:\n   - Select the JPEG images you want to combine.\n   - Double-click to open them in Preview (they should open in the same window as separate tabs).\n\n2. **Select All Thumbnails**:\n   - In the sidebar, select all the thumbnails of the images you want to combine (use `Cmd + Click` to select multiple).\n\n3. **Drag and Drop into One Document**:\n   - Drag the selected thumbnails onto the main Preview window to combine them into a single document.\n\n4. **Export as JPEG or PDF**:\n   - Go to `File > Export`.\n   - Choose the format (JPEG or PDF) and save the file.\n\n### Using Automator (For Advanced Users)\n1. **Open Automator**:\n   - Launch Automator from the Applications folder.\n\n2. **Create a New Workflow**:\n   - Choose \"Quick Action\" as the type.\n\n3. **Set the Workflow**:\n   - Add actions like \"Get Specified Finder Items\" to select images, then use \"Combine PDF Pages\" to merge them.\n\n4. **Save and Use**:\n   - Save the workflow and use it to quickly combine images into a PDF.\n\n### Using Third-Party Apps\n- **PDF Expert**: Offers a simple drag-and-drop interface for combining and converting images to PDF.\n- **Adobe Acrobat Pro**: Advanced PDF editing, including combining images into PDFs.\n- **SmallPDF**: Online tool for merging PDFs and images (no installation required).\n\n### Command Line (Terminal)\nFor advanced users, you can use the `sips` and `convert` commands in Terminal to manipulate and combine images:\n```sh\n# Combine JPGs into a PDF\nsips -s format pdf *.jpg --out combined.pdf\n```\nAlternatively, install ImageMagick (via Homebrew) and use:\n```sh\nconvert *.jpg combined.pdf\n```\n\nChoose the method that best suits your needs!",
